      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Strict secular neutrality is not about favoring secular values over religious ones, but rather preventing the state from endorsing any specific doctrine, which inherently protects religious freedom by ensuring no group is favored or disfavored. If a government forces a religious group to act against their conscience, it is not neutral; it is actively violating their fundamental right to freedom of religion, which is the very principle the state must uphold. A healthy democracy requires the state to remain a neutral referee that protects the rights of all citizens, including religious ones, rather than acting as an agent of a particular worldview.",
